animal.description: What could possibly be better than a quiet, well mannered Shih Tzu? . . . Why . . . Two quiet, well-mannered Shih Tzu!! . . .  Well . . . quiet and well-mannered might be a stretch but at least I got the Shih Tzu part right!!  Meet Crissy and her son Clippy; two adorable tail-wagging sweethearts.  They arrived at the Safehouse on 05/26/2020 along with four of their brothers and sisters.  All six dogs came to us from a Missouri puppy mill (listed as one of the 50 worst mills in the country by the HSUS).  Mommy Crissy, born 04/12/2012, has a beautiful non-shedding cream coat with light tan markings and weighs 18 pounds.  Clippy, born 07/11/2018, has a soft thick non-shedding white coat with gray markings and weighs 20 pounds.  One of his eyes is drying up and shrinking; don’t know why . . . he could have been born that way or (more likely) injured by an infection at the mill.  His other eye is just fine; he finds the treat in my hand with perfect aim!!!  Adjusting to the good life has come easily to Clippy.  In addition to care and comfort, Clippy has discovered LOVE.  Imagine, in his two years of life, he never felt kindness or the gentle touch of a human hand.  Clippy will stand on his hind legs, wrap his front legs around my leg and look up in begging anticipation.  You can’t help but want to love him back, his gratitude is so apparent.  I reach down to massage his back, his kisses are non-stop (literally) and then he falls over for a tummy rub!  Lively and friendly, Clippy is the more outgoing of the two; Crissy, is quieter, just as friendly but more reserved, she prefers to hold back until Clippy sends the “all-clear” and then she joins in on the snuggles; a happy little girl with a very busy waging tail.  She has made wonderful progress and will come to me for hugs and body rubs. She loves to snuggle into a warm soft pile of blankets or a big fluffy pillow.  Crissy enjoys playing with stuffed toys, always checking the toy box, exploring the big yard, curious about everything.  Her favorite pastime is burying her toys, inside under beds and blankets or in corners and outside under leaves and dirt or snow.  Hurray for snow, toys buried in mud need constant washing.  Crissy and Clippy are lively and playful and thrive on affection.  They soak up love like a starving dog vacuums up food.  Having never worn a collar or harness, they do not know how to walk on leash and have never been exposed to the noisy rush of traffic; training will take time and patience.  Since all dogs need healthy exercise, going for walks will be one of the first learning experiences to be shared with their new family.  They are, of course, crate trained, but having lived their entire life locked in a barren wire cage, expecting them to spend hours in a crate is unfair; if you cannot find an alternative to crating them, then please do not apply to adopt them. They are doing well with house training (using wee-wee pads and a doggy door) but will need assistance adjusting to a normal household and schedule.  In a fenced-in yard without a leash, they will run and jump and even go potty but if a mill dog gets loose outside a secured area, it will likely run until it drops; catching the dog would be quite a feat.  They get along with small dogs, but have never experienced cats.  They will do best in an active adult’s only home or one with older children; living in a home with young children would be too overwhelming, but the attention of older children would definitely be welcome.  Clippy and Crissy are quite a pair, always together, if you hug one you have to hug the other (dog rules!).  Mill rescues really need to go into a home with another dog in residence; that is how they learn to be dogs but these two have developed a strong bond (mother and son) and will be adopted together. They have a lot to learn about being dogs but I have their TRUST and they have my love and hopefully, soon, a very special adopter to participate in one of the most joyful and rewarding experiences of your life . . . teaching a frightened being to love and trust, to play, enjoy the comfort of a soft bed, good food and that life is ok and humans are good. Clippy and Crissy are spayed/neutered, microchipped, current on all vaccines, heartworm and flea/tick preventative, and they have had a complete physical and dental.  Their combined adoption fee is $500. These two MUST be adopted together; they have a bond that we will not break
animal.name: Clippy & Crissy

animal.description:
I am a young girl at just a 5 months old and 34 pounds. Rumor has it, I'm a Labrador/Border Collie mix. But who really knows. I LOVE to snuggle and cuddle and enjoy playing with the other dogs in my foster home. I'm sweet, smart, fun and am the submissive one! My ideal home will have another playful dog and a fenced yard to play in. Because I am still a pup I need an active family who is home more often than not and would enjoy taking me on adventures! Children over 8 years old are just fine. Dog friendly cats are just fine too. 

To adopt Birdie visit our website for more details regarding our adoption criteria and complete the easy online no obligation adoption application at www.dsda.org/adopt. 

* Adoption Fees:

Puppies (12 months and under) - $325 (includes tax)

Dogs (over 12 months) - $275 (includes tax) 

Qualifications for Adoption: No dog is alike and each dog has different requirements based on breed, age, energy level and life experiences. DSDA is very careful to place our dogs in homes that we believe are the best fit for the dog based on our experience with each dog. All of our dogs live in foster homes which allows us the opportunity to learn about their individual needs. 


	Must be 21 years or older with identification showing present address.
	Must have the knowledge and consent of all adults living in the household.
	Vet checks are required. All resident animals must be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations and on monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventative (if applicable).
	Must receive proof of pet deposit and lease allowing pets if renting.
	Willingness and capacity to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment and responsible care for a pet.
	Applicant is home more than not.
	Any poisonous plants must be removed from the yard before the home visit.
	Home visit is required. For this reason, we adopt locally in the Dallas and immediate surrounding areas.

animal.description: Katie Hepburn had to leave the love of her life when he could no longer care for her. For the past couple of years, they have both been living on the streets, so she was with him 24/7...and she liked that. She was hearbroken as was he...she cried quite a bit. When she's unhappy, she will bark, but she tends to be very happy when she's with her person...so if you're someone who is retired or simply home most of the time, Katie could brighten up your life! We were told she is not spayed, but at her age the vet suggested we not put her through such rigorous surgery.

animal.description:
Diamond is a 1-year-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and spayed/neutered. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. 

Diamond has been diagnosed with a congenital (present from birth) heart abnormality known as subaortic stenosis (SAS). This condition is due to the abnormal development of the heart tissue lying below the aortic valve. The abnormal conformation of this area causes the aortic valve to be leaky. Even though Diamond’s SAS is diagnosed as mild, her cardiac veterinarian recommends rechecking her echocardiogram in one year. Animals affected with SAS of this degree usually live a very normal life, and no treatment is needed at this time. Diamond’s cardiac veterinarian recommends feeding a diet that meets the WSAVA guidelines (Purina, Royal Canin, Eukanuba, Iams, or Hillls Science Diet).

We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at K-9adopt@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Barney
Estimated Breed : Labrador Retriever Mix
Approximate Age: 4 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 63 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Barney is a handsome active boy who is ready and waiting for his forever home. Barney absolutely loves car rides and will gladly jump in and go on any adventure with you. He is also sweet and affectionate once he gets to know you. Barney loves being near his people, but isn't constantly in your face but would make a great bud for your home office. He barely snores during your Zoom calls. Barney does ok with other dogs on leash, and around them, but has gotten into a scuffle in his foster home over a door bell and high excitement situation so he would prefer to be your one and only!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description: Meet Toby! Toby is a beautiful 10 month old male Blue Heeler. He weighs around 36lbs and we believed he was dumped out in rural MS. He came up to a woman's house looking for refuge and refused to leave. The woman had many outdoor cats and he scared them all off, so she threatened to shoot him if no one came to get him. Our rescue partners picked him up and he has been loving life in a foster home, where he is being given food, attention and a safe, warm place to sleep. Toby is house trained, has a medium energy level and is projected to be no more than medium sized when fully grown. His foster mom says, "He is a great dog. He will make a very loyal companion as he likes to be with his people. He will stay close when walking outside and he goes to the door when he needs to go potty. He is super smart and is learning commands." He is slow to warm up to other dogs, but had a proper introduction with the female dog at the foster home and they play together. He doesn't like dogs that get in his face or run right up to him. Toby is fully vetted and neutered. If you're interested in adopting this loyal, sweet boy, please apply at www.charliescrusaders.org

animal.description:
Humane Society/SPCA of Nelson County - ALMOST HOME

29 Stagebridge Road, Lovingston, VA 22949

Phone: 434 263-7722
Email: pets@nelsonspca.org

IMPORTANT!!! PLEASE READ

Posted animals are physically located at the above address except when indicated with the following notations after the animal's name:

Animal Name (FC=initials) -- indicates the animal is living in Foster Care. To meet the animal, please contact the foster directly when contact information is provided; otherwise call the shelter at 434 263-7722.

Animal Name (COURTESY) - this animal is posted as a public courtesy using information provided by the owner. Our shelter does not own or guarantee the information provided by the owner to be complete and accurate. Also, adoption does not involve our shelter but is strictly between the adopter and the owner.

LOVES PEOPLE AND A GOOD GAME OF CHASE!!!DATE: FEB 2, 2021(by Sigrid)
Dixie is a perky, young thing that seems to know she is pretty darling. To see her strut about on her stubby legs, no one would argue her adorableness. She wears a fawn coat, and it looks like black lipliner has been applied to her mouth. She was surrendered as a chow mix but looks more like a miniature Old Yeller type (small black mouth cur). Whatever she is, her muggy face is as cute as it gets.

Our Veterinarian estimates her to be about 8 months old, and she weighs in at 37 pounds, the perfect package-a small medium. She tested positive for Lyme Disease and is being treated now. Dixie has behaved friendly toward the other dogs at Almost Home, and when visiting the Vet's office for her exam, she had a great playtime with a few dogs there. When she met with our cats (in cages), her attitude was inquisitive but respectful.

Dixie likes all people and is always ready for a good game of chase. Toys make her get spunky, and when she gets the zoomies and goes flying around the yard at full speed, occasionally tagging you to play too, you can't help laughing out loud at her pure unbounded glee. This girl is very athletic and deceptively strong for her size.

If you are searching for a Valentine to lavish love upon, I don't think you'll find anyone more receptive than Dixie. She is waiting to give her heart to someone who wants puppy love that will last for a lifetime.

Dixie will do best with young folks, or active people, willing to teach her the things she needs know to be a good housemate and a well-mannered doggie citizen.

NOTE: All animals are spayed/neutered as soon as practical after arriving at our facility unless there is a medical issue that may cause a delay or they are too young to be spayed/neutered. VOLUNTEERS and DONATIONS NEEDED. Visit our website for more info: http://nelsonspca.org

Well . . . life didn't start off too great for us. We are a litter of 9 sweet boxer mix puppies. We were wet and cold for the first 8 weeks of our life. But, our lives have turned around now. We made it to Polk County Humane Society and we'd LOVE to be your VALENTINE for the best Valentine's Day ever. I'm hoping you are the ONE for me!

 You can find the online application for me at polkcountyhumanesociety.org/adopt. I will need to be brought back to the shelter one time to finish all of my vaccinations and neuter/spay, but that is all included in my adoption fee - so I'm the best Valentine you could ever give yourself!

animal.description:
Hello!  My name is Marley,  and I'm a male mixed breed dog born in June of 2019.   

My adoption fee is $175.

Hanover Humane will only be adopting me to a home in Hanover County, Virginia or a locality that is part of the Richmond, Virginia metropolitan area.

I'm an energetic, social, active, and playful guy and I'm seeking an energetic, social, active, and playful owner to keep me company - NO COUCH POTATOES. My favorite activity is to play tug - but I'm up for pretty much anything as long as I can be with my people. Unless you live a very active lifestyle and are willing to take me on multiple long walks daily, I'll probably need a fenced yard to burn off my energy(but you still gotta play with me).

 I've been neutered/spayed, am current on all of my vaccinations (DHLPP, Bordetella and Rabies), tested for heartworms (and am negative) and put on heartworm preventative, and microchipped.  My new owner will receive a month of free pet health insurance at adoption. 

If you are interested in me or want to meet me, please submit an adoption application at www.hanoverhumanesociety.org and you will be contacted to schedule an appointment.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Ashley (ha.evans@yahoo.com) for more information about this pet.
Online Adoption Application 
Squishy face cutie!!Luc is a young male probably large breed puppy - guessing shepherd mix of some sort and hes around 5 months old. Being a young pup, Luca will need an active home with plenty of time with his humans and space for excercise, play and socializing. His approved adopter will need to have time, patience, financial resources and interest to care for, provide proper veterinary care and work on positive reinforcement training to teach him all he needs to know to be a perfect little gentleman: potty training, crate training, leash walking and general good dog manners.
CARE's adoption fee is $250 for dogs/puppies and $100 for cats/kittens and an additional $150 neuter deposit will be required for any animals adopted prior to their spay/neuter surgery (and the deposit will be refunded when the approved adopter brings the animal to his/her CARE vet appointment in COLUMBUS, INDIANA once scheduled). All CARE animals arrive in their forever homes current on age appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, as well as microchipped and spay/neutered (or scheduled for the same). If you are interested in adopting or meeting a CARE animal, the FIRST STEP is to complete and submit an online adoption application through care.rescuegroups.org.

CARE is an all-volunteer and foster-based rescue organization. We do not have a shelter facility and do not have any employees monitoring inbound applications and emails. Applications are reviewed by each animal's volunteer foster home. It may be several days before you hear from this animal's foster home. Thank you for your patience and understanding as our foster volunteers work to navigate a very high volume of inbound adoption applications.

animal.description:
***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them***

Jesse is in Houston TX and can transport to the PNW mid February 

Jesse, male, 4 years old, pitbull, 43 lbs. We found out about Jesse when one of our friends called to say he was being given away at a gas station. Thankfully our friend's son was able to scoop him and give him a safe place to crash. 

Jesse is very playful and has a lot of wiggly butt energy. He is very playful and has a lot of energy. He is also very cuddly and loves to snuggle. 

He walks well on leash, but tends to pull. He can also get mouthy in a puppy/playful way and will need some training in this area. 

Jesse is a great listener and is highly trainable. He loves riding in the car. He is crate trained and house broken. When he first arrived to the foster home he had some accidents. With routine and consistency he learned to do his business outside. It's possible after transport he could regress and have a few accidents. Once he learns the routine in your home this will quickly resolve. 

Jesse is dog friendly and has been around dogs of all sizes. He would very much like to play and would love a four legged friend. He can get a little carried away when he plays and can play rougher so we think he would do best with a dog around his size or larger. He has never hurt the small dogs in his foster home but he gets super excited. 

Jesse has been around a 12 year old child and does really well. He is jumpy and has a lot of energy. We recommend a home with kids 10 years and older. 

Jesse is a really sweet boy despite the transitions in his life. He is looking for a family who can be patient and work on basic training. He is very friendly and wants a forever home.

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. ***

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for the dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Thanks for your interest in a pet from A.R.F.! If you see a pet here, they are still available for adoption and you should apply through our adoption application on our website at https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/application/
Olive is a 1 year old female miniature beagle who weighs in at 16 pounds. She is a very sweet and affectionate miniature beagle. Playful, young and curious, she enjoys exploring and meeting new people and other animals. Olive does fine in her crate, where she spends the night since she is still working on being house trained. So far she does not bark, but will bay mournfully if you leave the house or to be let in from outside. Olive comes when she is called and is eager to please. She will follow you around the house but loves lap time and couch time best of all. Snuggle up with this sweet companion any time of the day she'll keep your heart warm as well as your lap.

Olive is micro-chipped, up to date on all vaccinations, and spayed. Her new family will be required to complete a basic obedience course of their choosing.

Olive's adoption fee is $350. A meeting will not be scheduled until you have an approved application, so if you're interested in adopting Olive fill out an Online Application today!

Once your application has been approved, an ARF volunteer will contact you to arrange a meeting.

Thank you for considering a rescue pet from A.R.F.-Animal Rescue Foundation! We are
based in Wheaton, IL and conduct adoption events in the DuPage County area. If you are interested in adopting one of our pets, please submit an adoption application at https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/application/

Adoption appointments are scheduled based on the order of applications received, so submit your application early! Submitting an application does not commit you to any animal but does get you a head start with the adoption approval process. Due to a high volume of applications, we are often unable to respond to questions or schedule meetings until your application has been approved. More information about our adoption process can be found on our website here: https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/

As an all-volunteer, foster home-based organization, A.R.F. Animal Rescue Foundation does not have a facility where applicants can visit our animals. Please visit https://www.arf-il.org/events/ for a list of our upcoming adoption events.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, not shop!

animal.description: What could possibly be better than a quiet, well mannered Shih Tzu? . . . Why . . . Two quiet, well-mannered Shih Tzu!! . . .  Well . . . quiet and well-mannered might be a stretch but at least I got the Shih Tzu part right!!  Meet Crissy and her son Clippy; two adorable tail-wagging sweethearts.  They arrived at the Safehouse on 05/26/2020 along with four of their brothers and sisters.  All six dogs came to us from a Missouri puppy mill (listed as one of the 50 worst mills in the country by the HSUS).  Mommy Crissy, born 04/12/2012, has a beautiful non-shedding cream coat with light tan markings and weighs 18 pounds.  Clippy, born 07/11/2018, has a soft thick non-shedding white coat with gray markings and weighs 20 pounds.  One of his eyes is drying up and shrinking; don’t know why . . . he could have been born that way or (more likely) injured by an infection at the mill.  His other eye is just fine; he finds the treat in my hand with perfect aim!!!  Adjusting to the good life has come easily to Clippy.  In addition to care and comfort, Clippy has discovered LOVE.  Imagine, in his two years of life, he never felt kindness or the gentle touch of a human hand.  Clippy will stand on his hind legs, wrap his front legs around my leg and look up in begging anticipation.  You can’t help but want to love him back, his gratitude is so apparent.  I reach down to massage his back, his kisses are non-stop (literally) and then he falls over for a tummy rub!  Lively and friendly, Clippy is the more outgoing of the two; Crissy, is quieter, just as friendly but more reserved, she prefers to hold back until Clippy sends the “all-clear” and then she joins in on the snuggles; a happy little girl with a very busy waging tail.  She has made wonderful progress and will come to me for hugs and body rubs. She loves to snuggle into a warm soft pile of blankets or a big fluffy pillow.  Crissy enjoys playing with stuffed toys, always checking the toy box, exploring the big yard, curious about everything.  Her favorite pastime is burying her toys, inside under beds and blankets or in corners and outside under leaves and dirt or snow.  Hurray for snow, toys buried in mud need constant washing.  Crissy and Clippy are lively and playful and thrive on affection.  They soak up love like a starving dog vacuums up food.  Having never worn a collar or harness, they do not know how to walk on leash and have never been exposed to the noisy rush of traffic; training will take time and patience.  Since all dogs need healthy exercise, going for walks will be one of the first learning experiences to be shared with their new family.  They are, of course, crate trained, but having lived their entire life locked in a barren wire cage, expecting them to spend hours in a crate is unfair; if you cannot find an alternative to crating them, then please do not apply to adopt them. They are doing well with house training (using wee-wee pads and a doggy door) but will need assistance adjusting to a normal household and schedule.  In a fenced-in yard without a leash, they will run and jump and even go potty but if a mill dog gets loose outside a secured area, it will likely run until it drops; catching the dog would be quite a feat.  They get along with small dogs, but have never experienced cats.  They will do best in an active adult’s only home or one with older children; living in a home with young children would be too overwhelming, but the attention of older children would definitely be welcome.  Clippy and Crissy are quite a pair, always together, if you hug one you have to hug the other (dog rules!).  Mill rescues really need to go into a home with another dog in residence; that is how they learn to be dogs but these two have developed a strong bond (mother and son) and will be adopted together. They have a lot to learn about being dogs but I have their TRUST and they have my love and hopefully, soon, a very special adopter to participate in one of the most joyful and rewarding experiences of your life . . . teaching a frightened being to love and trust, to play, enjoy the comfort of a soft bed, good food and that life is ok and humans are good. Clippy and Crissy are spayed/neutered, microchipped, current on all vaccines, heartworm and flea/tick preventative, and they have had a complete physical and dental.  Their combined adoption fee is $500. These two MUST be adopted together; they have a bond that we will not break
animal.name: Crissy & Clippy

animal.description: Beautiful Jenny found herself in GA all alone and scared. As soon as I saw this baby I knew I had to Rescue her. Jenny made her way to NJ Jan 22, 2021. She had to finish her shot series and now that is behind her she is looking for her forever home. Yes, you read it correctly - She is a German Shepherd / Chihuahua mix! She is fully grown or almost there and she weighs in just around 20lbs. She is fluffy like a German Shepherd and Super Sweet as well. She only wants to be loved and cuddled. Jenny gets along and is non reactive to the cats in our household. She is just about housebroke and loves to play. She is Super Speedy and would need a fenced in yard in order to do her daily zoomies. Sable in color. If you are interested please email me at mtngirl4ever60@gmail.com for an application. DO NOT FILL OUT THE MISSFIT ANGELS APP ON PETFINDER. This is for another rescue partner in MN. We are located in NJ. You can also feel free to text at 856-285-8502

animal.description:
***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them***

Jesse is in Houston TX and can transport to the PNW mid February 

Jesse, male, 4 years old, pitbull, 43 lbs. We found out about Jesse when one of our friends called to say he was being given away at a gas station. Thankfully our friend's son was able to scoop him and give him a safe place to crash. 

Jesse is very playful and has a lot of wiggly butt energy. He is very playful and has a lot of energy. He is also very cuddly and loves to snuggle. 

He walks well on leash, but tends to pull. He can also get mouthy in a puppy/playful way and will need some training in this area. 

Jesse is a great listener and is highly trainable. He loves riding in the car. He is crate trained and house broken. When he first arrived to the foster home he had some accidents. With routine and consistency he learned to do his business outside. It's possible after transport he could regress and have a few accidents. Once he learns the routine in your home this will quickly resolve. 

Jesse is dog friendly and has been around dogs of all sizes. He would very much like to play and would love a four legged friend. He can get a little carried away when he plays and can play rougher so we think he would do best with a dog around his size or larger. He has never hurt the small dogs in his foster home but he gets super excited. 

Jesse has been around a 12 year old child and does really well. He is jumpy and has a lot of energy. We recommend a home with kids 10 years and older. 

Jesse is a really sweet boy despite the transitions in his life. He is looking for a family who can be patient and work on basic training. He is very friendly and wants a forever home.

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. ***

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for the dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Jojo is a 6 year old, 70 pound sweetie that is looking for a new home. Unfortunately Jojo’s dog buddy at home has a permanent injury that makes it impossible for them to be together and so Jojo isn’t getting the inclusion in the family that she loves so much. Jojo is an American Bulldog, spayed, up to date on all vaccines and heartworm treatment. She has had annual exams and has no medical issues.

Jojo loves running and is a good jogging partner. She loves toys/bones to chew on. She has medium energy, enjoys lounging around in the sun but will play fetch in an instant. She has grown up with another female dog in the house and has never had any issues. She is a little picky about her other doggy friends but tends to do best with other females. She has never had any toy/food aggression. We can freely take things in and out of her mouth without worry. Even my 3yr old can and she doesn’t bat an eye.

She is goofy, uncoordinated and HAPPY. She does not like cats or small animals. She LOVES children and would do best in a home with children 12 yrs old and up mainly because she isn’t aware of her size and at 70lbs her playing can easily bump most small children to the ground and scare them. Jojo loves belly rubs and will lay on the couch all day if you let her.

If you are interested in meeting JoJo please contact her current owner Paige (owner) 757-769-1315 paigerosekopf@gmail.com

A small rehoming fee is required and will be donated to a local rescue.

animal.description: 02/02/21 Maggie was returned to the shelter after a short adoption. The owner could not provide the excerise Maggie needs. Maggie is used to going on daily runs and would love someone to go skiijoring, bikejoring or just plain running with her. She is a very intellegent dog that knows many commands! She has been through multiple dog training classes and loves to learn new things. Maggie is said to love going to the dog park and gets along well with the other dogs. 01/20/21 Maggie, previously known as Artemis, was surrendered back to the shelter after biting a child in the home. She is said to to have many husky characteristics like digging, jumping on people, and rough when playing. She is housebroken. Maggie also loves going on car rides! Maggie has a lot of energy and enjoys going on long runs; she also recently started skijoring training. Maggie is very intelligent and needs an owner that will keep her body and mind active! In her previous home Maggie completed several basic and higher level obedience classes! She is said to be nice with children just has a low threshold, she is wary of men and is more friendly with women. Although Maggie likes people she also enjoys her space and that is something that her new owners should be aware of and respect. Maggie is said to not be the nicest with other dogs, especially other female dogs, and has a high prey drive. Because of her previous history Maggie is restricted to live in a house with no children 12 and younger. 09/17/19 (Maggie) Artemis was originally brought to the shelter as a stray so not much is known about her past. While at the shelter Artemis has been friendly with her animal tenders and the general public. She seems to be a high energy dog who enjoys digging complex holes in her yard, so she may be able dig her way out of a yard! Huskies are a very high energy breed who can often times get themselves into trouble by chewing up things that they shouldn't and being quite excellent escape artists! They need a lot of strenuous daily exercise to keep them happy and content!

animal.description: Hi I'm Tiger! I'm what they call an ambivert. I enjoy being with people and can be outgoing, but there are times when I just want to have some me time by exploring my surroundings or binge watching my favorite show. Right now I will need a home without children under the age of 12. I would also be better suited for a home with a fenced in yard rather than an apartment. Tiger is a Diamond Dog and will be shown by appointment only. Diamond Dogs are dogs that are currently receiving special training from staff and volunteers through our behavior modification program. If you are interested in learning more about this animal, please fill out an application by clicking here . Be sure to include Tiger A1362415 when filling out the survey. After reviewing your application, we will only be reaching out to you if the animal is a good fit for your home.

animal.description: Lil Man does not meet a person that is not instantly his friend. This happy go lucky, dancing all around guy, is looking for a place that he can call his forever home. Lil Man may have a big personality but he only weighs in at a little over 9 pounds, but don't tell him that he thinks he is a big guy. It is unknown how he is with children and cats, and if you have a dog at home we would recommend a meet and greet just to ensure their personalities mesh well together. Lil Man's adoption fee is $150. which covers core vaccines according to shelter protocol, 1 year rabies vaccine, deworming, heartworm and tick testing, and heartworm preventative. Lil Man is also neutered and microchipped. If you are interested in Lil Man please email the Canine Department at jrein@carrollcountymd.gov to request an application for him. Once applications are approved, we will then reach out to the approved adopter to arrange a meet and greet appointment.

Lola is 4 years old and weighs 61lbs. She is spayed, microchipped, and tested NEG for HW. animal.description: Weight: 27.7 pounds Good in a home with: Older children, other dogs Good in a home without: Young kids Meet Kiba! This sweet boy can be a bit shy when he meets new people, but really wants to be friends! Kiba can be a bit uncomfortable for some handling. Because of this, we believe he'd do best in a house with older children. Kiba has gotten along with the other dogs here at the shelter, but should meet new canine companions one-on-one to ensure they are a good match. Like all dogs, Kiba would benefit from positive, reward-based training classes to help him be the best he can be! This pup will require guidance and supervision learning to use the bathroom outside only, but our staff can give you tips to help with this.

animal.description: Hello, I'm Luna! I'm an extremely friendly girl looking for a new family! I love jumping up and giving kisses to friends and strangers alikelots of kisses! Lots and LOTS of kisses!! Im great with people, and Im even great with some dogs, too (have you met my son, Gucci - A0320023?). The staff here at Peggy Adams say that I'm a good girl and a good listener. I can sit and I know some words, I like going for walksI do it all! If youre looking for a lovely lady who will be by your side whether youre exercising, watching TV, or eating dinner, then consider adopting me, Luna, today! I'm part of the Grey Whisker Club, a program that places senior pets in loving forever homes. Adopt me and the shelter will provide a waived adoption fee and an ID tag, as well as yearly wellness exams, monthly flea and heartworm preventatives, and annual vaccinations for the rest of my life. Speak with an Adoption Coordinator to learn more. Senior pets make the best pets!

Cullen is the heart shaped nose cutie you need in your life! This handsome Terrier mix is 2 years old, weighs about 55 pounds and has been a gem in his foster home. Cullen is a superstar! He loves his crate and sleeps there perfectly through the night, he’s great on a leash and hasn’t had any accidents in his foster home. For the most part Cullen is pretty laid back. He’s been very sweet with his fosters, and even a little shy since coming from the shelter, but has been opening up. He gets very excited when he meets other dogs on walks that he can play with. He loves other dogs his size and smaller. It’s been great watching this boy blossom and grow more confident around his fosters, and we can’t wait to find his forever home.

Apply to adopt at rescuecity.nyc/adopt! 

We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

animal.description:
Cauldron is looking for a fetch partner. Someone to throw his ball again and again, please. He is happy to return it, place it at your feet or even in your hand if you don't feel like bending over to pick it up. He will oblige with panache and that look (see above). 

We're not exactly sure of his breed make-up, but he has the play style, intensity and sensitivity of the herding breeds (Border Collie, Kelpie, etc.). Speaking of sensitive, Cauldron can be a little shy and wary of new people at first, but once he gets to know someone, he shows his playful and affectionate side. When he is unsure of someone or something (sometimes other dogs) he gives 'the stare' which can be intimidating for the receiver. Because of these traits: sensitivity, shyness, wariness and staring, we would NOT recommend a home with children. Signals could too easily get crossed and messages misinterpreted.

Even so, Cauldron is a fairly straight forward kind of guy, and although it might take him a little time to open up, he shows great potential for learning and should blossom out with continued training and engagement. He shows true promise and as he matures, he might just make the perfect canine partner.

He was released from our search dog training program because of indications of arthritis (elbow) on his x-rays. The search work that our dogs train for requires lots of high-impact physical activity (jumping up and down from heights, running on uneven surfaces, lateral moves and other activities hard on joints). He shows no outward signs and other than limiting high impact activities, he would benefit from lots of physical activity such as hiking, walking, swimming, toy play and any low-impact dog sport.

This seriously amazing fetcher is waiting for you to throw the ball for him!

Cauldron is one year and two months old and weighs 44 pounds. He will be neutered before he is released and is up to date on all vaccinations.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Name: Bruno

DOB: 12/22/2011

Weight: 20 lbs

Adoption Fee: 125.00

Hi! My name is Bruno and I'm a 9 y.o. schnauzer-poodle mix. I have a schnauzer body and poodle hair, so I'm likely hypoallergenic (though not 100% guaranteed). Don't let my age fool you, we can live to 15 years old, so I have many good years ahead of me. I did lose one eye last year and I'm still getting used to life without it, so I prefer a quiet house without too many sudden movements (no young children or dogs who want to play). I live with an energetic Chihuahua now and I don't mind him because he leaves me alone, but I would prefer to be an only child (though I could learn to live with another quiet dog). Slow intros with any dog (resident or not) is a must.

I've been living with my foster family for about four weeks now and it took a couple weeks, but I fell in love HARD. I now follow them everywhere, quietly lay at their feet when they're working, and cry quietly for about ten min whenever my foster mom or dad leaves. After that, I just go lie down and wait for them to come home, even if they're gone a few hours. So you don't need to worry about me destroying anything and I haven't had a single accident in the house. My little tail wags so fast when they come home, sometimes I think it will wag right off! Loyalty and affection are my superpowers.

I've only been in MN for one year, and I have secrets from the before times that make it hard for me to warm up to you. So please be patient with me - no pets for the first couple weeks to be safe, just let me hang out around you. I'm totally fine with visitors to the house, I just ask them not to pet me (even if I'm staring up at them forlornly, practically begging for pets). If someone pets me who I don't trust, I might growl at them and I've even bitten before. My foster family started me on anti-anxiety meds recently and they think that will help a lot! Once I trust you though, it's game on! I want you to pet me ALL the time. I'll cuddle up next to you on the couch and be your best friend, I promise! I just need a forever family who is willing to be patient and allows me the space to love them on my own terms. I get attached easily, so it should only take a couple weeks until we're best friends.

I don't like to be approached from under the chin, so my foster momma gently twists my collar around so my leash can be attached on the top (I'm not a fan of harnesses yet - but maybe someday!). I LOVE walks, but I get a little jumpy and growly around other dogs, so we try to cross the street if we see another dog coming (the meds may help with that too!). I also love, love car rides, so if you want to take me to a less populated place to walk sometimes, I would love that! I'm 9 y.o. so I don't need a ton of exercise, but you'd be surprised how much energy I still have! A forever home that could walk me one mile every day, or two miles every other day, would be perfect. Exercise helps with my little bouts of anxiety.

If you're willing to take a chance and love me, I will return that love to you 100 fold. Because I'm a little slow to warm up, my foster momma would prefer you to meet me a couple of times, maybe go for a walk with me around our neighborhood. I live in S. Mpls now, so local applicants (or those willing to drive to come meet me at least twice) are preferable.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies:

animal.description:
PLEASE READ ALL THE INFORMATION IN THE DOG'S PROFILE, AS WELL AS THE INFORMATION ON OUR WEBSITE, www.niagaradogrescue.org , BEFORE EMAILING US WITH QUESTIONS. OUR VOLUNTEERS USE UP VALUABLE TIME ANSWERING QUESTIONS WHERE THE ANSWERS ARE READILY AVAILABLE ON THE WEBSITE. 
SINCE WE ARE ENTIRELY VOLUNTEER RUN AND RECEIVE A HIGH VOLUME OF APPLICATIONS, IT MAY TAKE AT LEAST 2-3 WEEKS BEFORE AN ADOPTION TEAM MEMBER CAN RESPOND TO YOUR APPLICATION. PLEASE BE PATIENT.
WE ARE FOSTER BASED, THEREFORE WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY.  MEET & GREETS FOR DOGS IN CANADA WILL NOT BE ARRANGED UNTIL AN ADOPTION APPLICATION IS APPROVED. THANK YOU!!!

Please visit our website at http://www.niagaradogrescue.org or apply for adoption at http://www.niagaradogrescue.org/adoption/


Name: Ari Weight: 50lbs (and gaining)
Age: 3 years
Gender: female
Spayed/neutered: yes
Breed: Boxer Mix
Color: Black and white

Neck Size: 14”
Height (from top of head) 27”
Length (nose to base of tail) 37”
Crate size: 42” at least, here in 48”, allows room for water pail

Good with women: yes
Good with men: yes
Good with kids: ? no children here
Good with other dogs: yes
Good with Cats:? No cats here
House trained: yes
Crate Trained: yes
Energy level: medium
Can be touched/ handled: yes
Barker: not really but is vocal when she wants attention
Flight Risk: medium initially, loves people
Food Aggressive: none, she has been fed by herself, takes treats nicely, have petted her while she was eating and put hands in food bowl
Current Food: Purina ProPlan Sensitive Skin and Stomach, salmon 2.5 C twice a day plus an extra cup when I am home in the middle of the day
Walks on a leash: yes, reluctant to potty on leash
Leash reactive to dogs or people: no
Rides well in the car: was crated in car, seems to want to get in my car and ride
Destructive: no, has chewed some small holes in her blankets
Needs a home with a yard: yes, particularly until she potties well on a leash.
Needs a home with another dog: no. She is fine with dogs but much more focused on humans.
Can live in an apartment: no

This statuesque girl is beautiful inside and out. She leans into you when you pet her and really likes attention. Since she wants to please and is treat motivated, she learns quickly. She has not been mouthy but does like to tug on toys. We have been working on “drop it” and then having her move away from the toy before I pick it up to throw it again for her to fetch. She fetches balls and rubber stick toys.
She is not high energy but does take her a little bit to settle down. If you move your hands quickly or fuss, she ducks her head and looks concerned. She can jump like she has springs in her legs and her tail is like a whip. Her tail swings about the height of a toddler’s face.
After the first night, she has been great in her crate. During a recent thunderstorm, she was distressed but settled nicely when I moved her crate where she could see me. She does like to drag her blankets out of her crate and around with her. She had enjoyed a chew toy that incorporates some wood in it and she usually has it in her crate.
Here she is on a schedule to potty, especially mornings and evenings. She goes out to potty in the am, gets fed and then back out to potty in ~ 30 minutes. She goes out again mid-day. She goes out when I get home, gets fed and then back out in about 30 minutes. Tonight, as I was writing this, I realized I had not taken her back out after feeding her and she was standing by and looking at the doors so she may give you some cues. She also goes back out before bed

animal.description:
Meet Winter! This handsome boy is a 2-year-old, 60 pound Shepherd/Husky Mix who is great with other dogs and loves outdoor adventures! 
 
Winter’s foster family says that he loves to lounge around and is very chill in the home for the most part. Winter equally loves going on long walks in any weather, and being a couch potato all in one! Winter loves all dogs, no preference on gender, age, size, etc, and would do amazing in a home with another dog, he is on his best behavior when he has at least an hour or two of playing in the morning. He gets very attached to his humans but has started to venture around the house by himself. He does sleep in this crate but only if it’s in the bedroom with someone being around. With baby steps he is getting better with being left alone, and alone in his crate but will need a patient adopter who will continue to work with him on his separation anxiety. When he is nervous or over stimulated he starts chewing and getting mouthy (very much in a puppy way) but he is easy to train, understands commands and is treat motivated. Winter is goofy, talkative  an can be stubborn, very much like a Husky, but he is very smart and eager to learn, like a German Shepherd. He LOVES to play both by himself an with people/other dogs but can lounge all day on the couch once he's had enough physical and mental stimulation. Winter is the perfect pup to help you get some pep in your step but then come home and cuddle up with you for back to back nights of Netflix and chill!

Apply to adopt at rescuecity.nyc/adopt! 

We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

Thank you for wanting to give one of our adoptables a loving home! Please follow us on Instagram at @rescuecity for more adoptable updates!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Buck! I am about 8 months old, and arrived here at the shelter when my owner could no longer care for me. I am a super high energy boy and I LOVE people. I can get very overexcited to see you because I want to play! I think it’s a hilarious game to jump on every person I see, chase their shoes, and give them playful nips. I don’t really understand how to walk on a leash yet, and usually try to bite the leash or jump up on the person holding it. I need a forever home who is experienced with high energy dogs and has plenty of time and patience to help me learn my manners and practice calm, appropriate behavior. My home will need to have no children or cats, and large securely-fenced yard where I can run and play. 
 
My adoption fee is $150 (+ $20 county dog license, if residing within Jefferson County). I have been neutered, am up to date on my rabies and DAPP vaccines, and have been micro-chipped too! IF YOU ARE SEEING MY BIO, I AM STILL UP FOR ADOPTION - PLEASE FOLLOW THE DIRECTIONS BELOW.

ADOPTION PROCEDURE: HSJC is currently CLOSED to the public due to the pandemic. We are accepting applications for Buck, and you can submit one via our website here: https://hsjcwa.org/adopt-a-dog
We do not ship animals, and due to COVID and border issues cannot adopt to Canada at this time.

If we find an applicant who seems to match Buck well, we will contact you to schedule a time for you to meet her at our facility. If you have trouble submitting your application, please send an inquiry and we can email you one! Thank you!

Meet Oakley!
Oh sigh, this little doll is adorable! She is friendly, playful with other dogs and pretty well behaved for a puppy. She does have loads of energy and loves toys, fetch and walks.

animal.description:
BENTLEY is 10 years old and weighs 17 pounds.

I am a true beagle, and as a beagle I reserve the right to be inquisitive (I won't pry into your private affairs however), about yard smells, other animals and the whole, great world out there. After all, curiosity is the sign of intellect, and if there is one thing I am, it's intellectual. If I was a human being I think I might be teaching at Harvard. I also reserve the right to bay at the moon occasionally and certainly bark at other dogs until you let me sniff them. I'm fairly quiet and calm after I get to satisfy my curiosity. 

My main interest, after checking the world out, is to sleep - but, in comfortable places and boy am I good at finding those. The best places are: 
1. the couch 
2. the bed
3. under the covers in the the bed
4. in a 2-legged's lap 
5. on the dog bed with my 4-legged foster brother
Told you I was smart. When not napping I just lie quietly and watch the world around me with interest. I am a calm guy and will settle down quickly - even in a crate though, as I stated earlier, the bed is preferable. In fact, if I see you getting ready for bed I will be up there waiting for you - hahaha. I am great in the car too, but let me choose me own place to ride. And, as we know, never put me in the driver's lap. I value my life too much for that. 

I enjoy all manner and ages of human life forms. I am rather partial to men - don't know why. Maybe because I am a man too so can relate better to all that manly stuff? I was at the vet recently getting my teeth cleaned, my body vaccinated and chipped, they did something the people in the white coats called neutering. Not sure what that means, but parts of my undersides are sore now and the vet said something about my manhood. Hope it's all good whatever occurred down there.

Well, that's me: smart, curious and calm (after my curiosity is satisfied). I am now curious about my new forever home. Will it be you?


 
INTERESTED in BENTLEY? The first step is to fill out our online Adoption Application (address link below)

NOTE: All of our dogs live in foster homes so it is not possible to setup a meet and greet prior to submitting an adoption application. Filling out an application doesn't obligate you to adopt, but it does save your place in line if there are multiple people interested.
 
ADOPTION APPLICATION (Type or cut & paste the below website address into your browser): http://www.sdroregon.com/adoption-application.htm
 
If our Adoption Coordinator determines you are a good match they will contact you. This is a great opportunity for you to find out more about BENTLEY and decide if you would like to setup a meet and greet.  
 
ADOPTION FEE is $150, and there’s a 10% Discount for Senior Citizens and Veterans.
 
Learn more about the ADOPTION PROCESS here (Type or cut & paste the below website address into your browser): http://www.sdroregon.com/adoption-process.htm
 
We apologize, but we are not able to answer individual questions about our dogs. We are a small, all-volunteer organization and we receive hundreds of inquiries. If you want to learn more about a particular dog, then please submit an Adoption Application. If your application is chosen, you will have the opportunity to meet the dog and to get answers to all of your questions. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Tony is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Tony is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~4 years 
Weight: ~61lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Working on it - takes some time to settle, but overall doing well with crate training
Dog sociability: Selective with his dog friends and may be a match for some, but not all. He lives with a dog in his foster home and has done well with her, but is leash reactive on walks when he sees other dogs or people. He will benefit from a confident handler and continued leash training.
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Has done well with teenagers in his foster home. He's mouthy (play bites) so not recommenced for kids under 12.
Ideal home: Tony would love to live in a quieter neighborhood where he doesn't have to pass by a bunch of people or other dogs. He would love an adopter committed to working on training and helping to continue safe socialization. 

If you are looking for a sweet pittie baby, Tony is your man! He LOVES to cuddle and will curl up next to you all day and night if you let him. He is still young so he has some puppy energy and will need occasional play breaks. Tony is still working on playing politely, and can mouth when he gets too excited and can't contain himself. If you even look at the leash for too long he will start dancing around wanting to go for a walk. He can be food motivated and goes wild for meat but will also take any food like a refined gentleman if offered to him. Tony is a very loving dog and once you are his human he will love you blindly. He will follow you around the house, sleep next to you at night, and keep an eye on you when you go out together to make sure you are safe. Tony is looking for a home that will take his accepting love and give it back to him tenfold because that is what this sweet boy greatly deserves.

Tony's adoption fee is 300. He is neutered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. He will need a dental cleaning in the next 6 months which will be the adopter's responsibility. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

Xander is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Xander is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~2 years
Weight: ~50lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time to settle but overall doing great with his cratetraining
Dog sociability: Friendly with dogs on walks. Sometimes can be frustrated and may jump/pull when he sees another dog.
Cat sociability: Not a match
Kids: Not a match for young kids (he can be mouthy/play bites), but may do well with teenagers
Ideal home: Xander is an energetic dude that is looking for an active adopter committed to working on training for adolescent behaviors. He does very well when given daily mental and physical enrichment.

Xander is a happy go lucky, quick-learning, playful teenage pup looking for his forever home! He came to us from a shelter in Texas after he was found as a stray. He is truly the jack of all trades - housetrained, doing well with his crate-training, and likes to meet other dogs - what more could you ask for? Xander enjoys learning new tricks (he's learned sit, stay and down in a matter of a week!), going for walks around the neighborhood, cuddling up next to his human during his daily afternoon nap, accompanying people on car rides and watching himself in the mirror...can't blame him, he's pretty handsome! He is still a bit of a teenager and working on his table manners and learning what is and what is not a dog toy, etc. so he would do best with someone excited to train an intelligent pup!

Xander's adoption fee is 300. He is neutered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.See our story below:) Super sweet Terrier-Beagle and whatever mix siblings. They appear to be house broken at ourOur story:We were rescued in a hallway of an apartment with newborn puppies I animal control. on a five day stray hold then transported to this rescue thankfully:) where we felt safe and spoiled and our puppies thrived. The rescue after a few days found out we were rescued together so they put us back together in the same room. First they put us outside and when we saw each other we jumped up and down with joy! We ran around the yard kissing each other's faces our tails wouldn't stop wagging! Because we are so bonded and went through so much we want to be adopted together. We are very affectionate and friendly with our foster. Meet Kaya! Kaya is a stunning 1 year old Belgian Malinois mix! Kaya is the sweetest girl and has a very driven, eager to learn personality. Much like the breed, Kaya is very smart and is a very active dog. She enjoys working on commands, going on walks and romping around outside. Kaya is social and loyal! animal.description:
Meet Rocco! This handsome boy is ready for his next adventure! Rocco is an active and playful pup who is eager to go explore the world. He loves hiking and going to the beach as well as playing at the local dog park. Rocco will need an active family to keep up with him and help him burn his energy.

Rocco will require lots of mental stimulation in addition to physical exercise. He would benefit from dog sports (agility, nose work, trick training, etc.) as well as using puzzle toys and feeders as home. Rocco will keep you on your toes as he shows off his intelligence!

Rocco shows no signs of resource guarding or separation anxiety in shelter or in his previous home. He has not lived with other animals before but could live with dogs. He has no experience living with children but has done okay when visiting children, his bouncy exuberant behaviour does put him at risk of knocking kids down however it is not intentional.

We are still getting to know Rocco as this time, please check back for more information as we better understand his needs!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.gl=document.createElement('script');gl.src='https://secure.givelively.org/widgets/simple_donation/midwest-animal-rescue-services-puppy-rescue-of-minnesota.js?show_suggested_amount_buttons=false&show_in_honor_of=true&address_required=false&has_required_custom_question=null';document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0].appendChild(gl);

Adoption Fee: $550Scottie is still learning how to interact with other dogs so will need someone to patiently teach him that other dogs can be new fun friends.

Scottie is a fun little guy looking for his new best friend! He is a sweet loving dog. He does not jump up, however puts his paws up on your leg if he wants attention. He doesn't seem to sit very well to get his leash on. Rather he rolls on his back so you can rub his tummy. When he does sit, he sits like a puppy. He is a definite, definite lapdog will spend evening sitting with you or alongside you with his head in your lap.
He is not a begger, so no worries about your dinner plate! No whining or begging. What a good boy!

Scottie is a smart boy who can open doors if they are cracked just a little bit! He loves sniffing for walks and is past the puppy 'zoomies' stage. He loves sleeping in bed and will even cuddle under the covers! Perfect for a cold MN night for sure!

Scottie will go in a crate though he has a definite preference for a larger wire one vs a plastic crate. Once he's settled into the crate of preference, he's a 'very chill dog' and does fine.

He will bark when someone comes to the door, at sirens and loud trucks...and people walking along the sidewalk, however if he doesn't have access to a front window near a busy sidewalk, he's quiet. He only will bark if he can see people. :o)

He does fetch , that is a slow run, with toys and balls. He enjoys exploring new places and does well meeting new people. He's very respectful with his people and seems to intuitively know if he is welcome on a lap or should just reside in a vacant chair.
Interested in meeting this great little dog? Click the adopt button below.

or

PETFINDER VIEWERS: Find our applications at www.midwestanimalrescue.org

*The pet you are viewing is a rescued pet which is most often from an animal control facility and does not come with a pedigree. The breed(s) listed are our best guess and are in no way guaranteed. Sometimes the pets appear to be a particular breed(s) in the pictures we receive from our rescue partners and when they arrive we are surprised to see an entirely different breed(s) in person! If you choose to DNA test your adopted pet, test results may vary from company to company and our breed guess may not be reflected in those results as it is just that, our best guess. It is with deep longing that we wish there was a breed called "cute" as we believe all of our dogs would fall under this new breed classification!

//

animal.description:
PLEASE DO NOT ASK ABOUT AVAILABILITY OR EMAIL THROUGH PETFINDER or ADOPT-A-PET - WE CANNOT RESPOND - READ THE PROCESS BELOW.

If you're interested in any of our wonderful dogs, you must FIRST fill out an Adoption Application at our website listed below. Once we receive it, we'll forward it to the foster family for follow up. We are 100% foster based, so we don't have a facility. Review the process FAQ at our website.

Adoption applications can be found here: http://labrescuefresno.org/available-labs/adoption-application/

Adoption Fees Adult Dog (10 mos. - 7 years): $250.00 Puppy (9 mos. and under): $350.00 Senior (8 yrs. and up)/Special Needs Dog: $100.00

Jake - Black Male, Age 18 Month, 60 pounds

Are you looking for a handsome cuddler to add to your family? Do you want to look at beautiful, soulful brown eyes? Look no further than Jake (also known as Jake-y poo at his foster home).
Jake came to us when a good Samaritan in Tulare County picked him up as he was running in fear from other dogs. LRRF once again sprang to the rescue and saved this sweet boy. We do not know Jake's upbringing or background but from his time in his foster home we have learned Jake will need a special forever home. Jake is still a young dog and has not had much human contact. Jake is learning in his foster home how to communicate properly. He will need a family that has a strong human pack leader dedicated to his continued training and daily exercise.
Jake is a very smart boy; he has learned to potty outdoors, can walk nicely on a leash and is crate trained. He knows "sit", is working on "off", and is a quick learner who is attentive and inquisitive. He has lots of Lab energy but above all, he is a cuddler and would love nothing more than to rest his head on your lap and want to be with you wherever you goincluding the bathroom if you forget to close the door.
Jake will do best in a home with older children, and without cats or small dogs. He loves dogs his own size. This loving guy is ready for his forever family.
If you feel you are that strong pack leader and you'd like to add lovable Jake-y poo to your family, please fill out an application at www.labrescuefresno.org

If you are interested in adopting through Labrador Retriever Rescue of Fresno, you must first fill out an Adoption Application located at our website www.LabRescueFresno.org All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines including rabies; flea/tick topical drops, heartworm tested and microchipped. Thank you for opting to adopt!!
Adoption FeesAdult Dog (10 mos. - 7 years): $250.00 Puppy (9 mos. and under): $350.00Senior (8 yrs. and up)/Special Needs Dog: $100.00

Meet McIntosh! 

He is a 3-4 year old Pit Bull Terrier mix who weighs about 65 pounds. McIntosh is a very affectionate and friendly pup who loves attention! He enjoys walks outside and would likely make a great hiking buddy! He can be a bit dog selective, so he would need a slow introduction to new dogs. He loves treats and is always eager to learn some new tricks to show off. If there are kids in the home, he would prefer kids ages 10 and up. He is a goofy guy looking for his forever home. 

If McIntosh looks like the apple of your eye, give our adoption counselors a call at 234-212-9843 to schedule an appointment to meet him today!

animal.description:
Hey there! Shelby's the name!

I'm a big, goofy boy who absolutely loves pets and all of your attention. I also enjoy treats and playing with toys. The best part about toys is that I'm really good at entertaining myself! Sometimes I forget I'm a big guy and may end up in your lap sometimes! I'm a little clumsy and a little jumpy, so I'd prefer to live in a home with humans middle school age and older. I'm a bit selective about who my doggy friends are, so please bring your doggy to the shelter to meet me! I haven't even met you yet and I love you already! See ya soon!

I'm Beemer's Buddy! Thanks to Champman BMW Camelback, you can take me home for free!

Make an appointment to meet me at AAWL's Main Shelter!

25 N. 40th St
Phoenix AZ 85034

https://aawl.org/content/appointment-based-adoptions

AAWL recommends I live with humans MIDDLE SCHOOL AGE and OLDER.
AAWL thinks I am MUST MEET all dogs in the home prior to adoption. Please bring your dog here to the shelter to meet me!
AAWL thinks I am a DAILY WORKOUT, needing lots of exercise..
AAWL does not know if I can live with cats at this time.

animal.description:
Sophie is a 1 year old spayed female lab/terrier mix who weighs about 34 lbs. Sophie was rescued from an overcrowded high kill shelter after being dumped by her owner. Our hearts broke for this sweet girl as we saw the fear she experienced in the loud shelter. Now that she is safe with us we are beginning to see glimpses of her true self. Sophie is incredibly sweet, but is still very shy. She will need a patient family willing to give her time to settle in and learn that she is safe. It's clear she has never been on a leash and doesn't understand how it works. Sophie really lights up when she sees other dogs and loves meeting new doggie friends. She would love a confident canine pal in her forever home to help show her the ropes. With a little patience, kindness, and a lot of love we have no doubt this brindle beauty will flourish in her forever home; all she needs is a chance. Please help us find Sophie the forever home she's been dreaming of!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Follow us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets: https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

animal.description:
Weight: 67.20 lbs.

Adoption Price: $100

WANT TO TAKE ME HOME TODAY? SCHEDULE AND ADOPTION APPOINTMENT.
To Schedule An Adoption Appointment:
1. Fill out and submit our online Adoption Application.
2. Please only submit ONE Adoption Application. (Our Application is for general pre-approval, not for a specific adoptable animal).
3. Once received, the Allen County SPCA will review your application. Applications are reviewed in the order they are received.
4. We will contact you to let you know your Adoption Status and schedule an Adoption Appointment. Applications may take up to 1-2 days to process. Please give us a call at the shelter at 260-744-0454 if you have not heard back from us within 48 hours.
5. If you haven't found your perfect match at the shelter, that's okay too - pre-approved applications are valid for 6 months!

Come prepared! Please bring proof of a current rabies vaccine for all pets living in the home. If you have another dog, you are welcome to bring him or her with you so that we can safely perform a dog interaction.

Unfortunately, animals cannot be held for you.

A Special Note from the Allen County SPCA:
Remember, pets are a lifelong commitment. We at the Allen County SPCA ask that you take adding a furry family member to your home seriously, and do your research on the different breeds before adopting. We also ask that you are able to keep up on yearly vaccinations, monthly preventatives, a good diet, daily exercise, training, and most of all, LOVE. If you ever have an issue with a pet that you adopted, please contact us right away; we may be able to help, or we can put you in touch with someone who can. All set? Come in and adopt today!

animal.description: This cutie is on the shy side but will steal your heart with his sweet disposition!! Meet Chance, a six year old Boxer/Mt Cur mix that will need you to stop in a few times to visit before he will be able to head home. Building trust and comfort ability takes some time but once he is sure you are his friend he sticks close and loves affection. Once warmed up this guy is full of puppy energy and will bring a smile to your face as he romps and plays outside!! Chance has lived in a home with cats and enjoyed their company greatly in his previous home. He can also be shy around other dogs but with the right dog friend he might benefit greatly with his confidence. We think Chance would do best in a home with adults and kids over the age of 8. If you think you would love to give some confidence to this guy in your loving home apply for our Chance today!!

animal.description: Hi, I'm Redford. Obviously, I have rugged good looks, but more than that, I'm a surprisingly awesome cuddle buddy! The volunteers tell me I'm their favorite so I give them lots of hugs. I love all the people I meet, but I have been called a "ladies man". I only want human company, not other animals. I am good on leash, but I do need to keep working with my foster mom to learn to ignore other dogs on walks. I have very good manners, and am completely house trained. I will need to find a family who will continue my positive reinforcement training. Luckily, I'm very food motivated, so my training will be fun! Besides walks, playing with my toys, and snuggling in bed, I really love car rides. I would be a great road trip buddy! If you're looking for a big lovable dog to share your life with, fill out the application so you can meet me: hsnb.org/adoptions. Not to brag, but I will be an amazing best friend! PS. My adoption fee is only $75. Thank you. Primary Color: Tan Secondary Color: White Weight: 90lbs Age: 3yrs 5mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description: I'm Bear! I'm a tough little guy, hence the name. I am a survivor. I came into the shelter with some medical issues, a virus, a pretty impressively large tumour, but I've beat every obstacle life has thrown at me and now I'm thriving! I do have a big scar healing up on my back where my growth was removed, but every scar tells a story and mine tell a story of perseverance! My medical history aside, I'm an incredibly sweet and playful little guy. I can be pretty vocal when I want attention, I love to run, and I LOVE my food! Feed me and love me, and this is the start of a beautiful friendship between us. Think you have what it takes to be my new family and give me a much needed new lease on life? Apply for me today!
