animal.description:
Meet Lovable Lexi who was rescued from a rural area in North Carolina on private property. She will arrive just in time to be your Valentine xoxoxo. She, and her sibling Lucy, are thought be born in September of 2020. They are believed to be a mix of Lab / hound mix with their medium sized bodies, stunning eyes and beautiful fur. She is currently about 25 pounds and should be 40 - 45 pounds full grown.  Lexie is a bit of a "snuggler" and just loves those belly rubs.  She is so very sweet and smart.   She will be an amazing family dog and loyal companion.

They are very healthy, active and love to play. They will have 2 rounds of shots and have been dewormed upon arrival. They would be a perfect addition to any home.
Their adoption fee is $495, which also includes transportation and their two rounds of vaccines.Their adoption fee is $495, which also includes transportation and their two rounds of vaccines. 

IMPORTANT: This puppy has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

If they are listed on Petfinder, they are still available. We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for the family and most importantly, the puppy.  We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's physical appearance.  

Please visit snarrnortheast.org for the applications to adopt.  If you are interested in adopting any of the puppies our adoption fee is $495 and we do suggest putting a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application

**** The first step in adopting a puppy through SNARR Northeast is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org.  Please understand that at this time we are currently experiencing increased interest in our adoptable dogs/puppies, so if you are interested in adopting in a dog, the best thing to do is submit an adoption application ASAP. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. Please make sure to receive a receipt of confirmation after submitting your application to ensure that it has come through properly.****
animal.name: Lexie (NC)

He is great with some dogs and demanding and annoying to others. He is young and eager for a family that will guide him to grow and learn. He knows how to use doggy door and loves playing with toys .His house skills are pretty good, until there is food around.  Tony is not yet great with crating. He only uses it when food is being prepped. He is fed separately from other dogs. He shares the bed with his foster humans and siblings when it is bedtime. We are hoping for a dog savvy family with no children under 10 or an adult only home and fenced yard needed Tony would love a family who will continue working with him and learning with him.

Tony is spay/neutered, microchipped, current on vaccines, heartworm tested and on prevention. Adoption fee for Tony is $275. If you are interested in adopting Tony, please fill out an adoption application http://www.furgetusnotrescue.org/application.html .

animal.description:
WALKING ON SUNSHINE! KATIE’S STORY: For almost a year, senior KATIE, age 11, has waited at a shelter. She was given away by her family in late 2019. Only a few months later, in March 2020, KATIE was found alone in West Babylon and brought to Babylon Animal Shelter. Her owners were tracked down but the woman caring for her had broken her hip and her adult son didn’t want KATIE. For the second time in only a few months, she lost her home.

KATIE had us from her first approach. She led with an adorably wonky head tilt and bobbed like a boat riding gentle waves. She stepped as though delicate flowers were underfoot, laying each paw down gently in a prancing trot her body had adopted to balance a neurological trauma. Despite recently losing her lifelong home and navigating a physical disability in a shelter environment, KATIE is what might happen if sunshine were mixed with sugar.

The last of four long time shelter dogs we brought into our #OneLuckyPup program from BAS, we put KATIE through a day of testing, assessment and MRI at The Animal Medical Center, led by neurologist Dr. Abbie Lebowitz, where we learned KATIE had a stroke. This traumatic event left her with some sweet signature moves, but no serious damage. A CSF tap confirmed lack of disease and supports this diagnosis. Over 60% of dogs like KATIE who experience a stroke lack an identifiable cause and no increased risk of future strokes. What does this mean for KATIE? Well, nothing really. KATIE is just a senior dog in need of a loving home to live out her many golden years left. 

KATIE, mildly active, would enjoy a calmer home. She didn’t engage with other shelter dogs, likely because she feels physically limited, so her home should have no other pets. KATIE enjoys walks, being talked to, hanging with her peeps and cream cheese.

If you like Sunday morning bagels and can spare a schmear, head to mrbonesandco.org/adopt or email elli@mrbonesandco.org with questions. We’ll consider homes within a 5-hr drive of NYC or Wash DC, where her foster will take over in a few days. 

#AdoptKatieMBC

animal.description:
Refined and cultured is how my four legged friends describe me. The humans call me calm and well behaved. Either way, I'm a catch that will bring class and style to your home.

He is a wonderful dog that is super sweet and playful. He is good with cats and dogs. He loves his tennis ball but doesn't understand the concept of fetch yet. He enjoys laying down with his squeaky toys but does not chew on them for very
long and hasn't ripped any up. He does great on a leash and doesn't pull unless he really wants to sniff something in his path. When seeing other dogs on walks he doesn't even acknowledge that they are there he just keeps on walking. We have only heard him bark once, but he can be vocal if he is kept in a crate when nobody is in the room. We have only ever put him in the crate for training reasons. He is left out to roam free when there is nobody home and never tore up anything. The longest he was left home for was about 3 hours multiple different times. He is potty trained and shouldn't have any accidents as long as he is let outside. The only big issue we have had with him is that he will bolt out the front door. He has tried several times even with someone standing in the doorway. You must hold him or have him on a leash before opening the door. He ran from the kitchen out the front door in half a second and started walking down the neighborhood
before I caught him. He will not listen to you if you call him back. We did start training him using the words sit and wait before opening any door (bedroom, back, & front) and he did good, again make sure he is on the leash when opening the front door even when training. We also started teaching him "come" and he picked it up rather quickly. He is a stubborn dog and will require a bit of training just like any other dog, but he has the basics down and is willing to work for his treats. We have a 3ft chain link fence in the backyard, and he has not tried to jump over it or mess with any of our neighbor's dogs. He loves being outside. If you let him stay out there for hours he would lay down in the grass and enjoy the cold breeze. He sleeps in the room with us next to our bed with the door closed all night and doesn't make a peep. He does not scratch at the door or bark to be let out, as long as you are in the room with him he has zero problems. He will jump up in bed or on the couch and cuddle up next to you. He does very well
around food and does not try to sneak anything off your plate or beg at your feet. Iwould suggest he be with another dog that he can play with or a family that can play with him and take him on walks every day. He is a very good boy and will make a perfect dog if you are willing to give him the time he needs.
 Primary Color: Tri Color Secondary Color: White Weight: 55.5lbs Age: 2yrs 0mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

Noel was surrendered by her owner to No Kill Glynn County after being brought into a local vets office to be seen for her "slight hair loss". Noel had lived her short life constantly on a chain and she lived under the house. The owner knew that surrendering her was the best thing to do for the pup. 

Noel was then placed into one of our loving foster homes. With some time and a little love, Noel has completely healed. She has been completely vetted and is now spayed. She loves all people, does great with children, and gets along with other dogs. 

Since being with us she has been on flea/tick prevention as well as heartworm prevention. She has been tested for HW and is HW-. 

She is completely house trained and loves to snuggle up on the couch at her fosters house. 

If you are looking to add a furry member to your family, please consider Noel. Fill out an adoption application here: https://form.jotform.com/203216945213146

animal.description:
****Please do not send messages to the rescue asking if a dog is still available; if a dog is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO & FAQs BEFORE EMAILING THE RESCUE****

Hoss's owner reached out to SNARR NE to help rehome him safely.  His owner was very sad about rehoming him, but she has  5 other dogs, both male and female. Hoss has always gotten along with all of the other dogs in the house without incident, except for the latest addition to the family who was an unaltered male dog. Although Hoss gets along well with the other male dogs in the home, we will only be placing Hoss in a home without  another male dog. Hoss has lived in a home with racoons, skunks and opossums (his former owner is a wildlife rehabilitator). He also shared his home with a cat. Hoss is estimated to be 7 years old, but he still has playful spurts, especially when he sees kids. Because of his large size (he weighs just under 100 pounds), and his playful nature, we will not be adopting Hoss into a home with children. 

Hoss loves to lounge on a couch with his people. One of his favorite things to do is to go on a car ride. 

Hoss is heartworm positive, but has been on heartworm treatment. 

To apply to adopt Hoss, visit www.snarrnortheast.org/applications and submit an application. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING 
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder,  there are sometimes discrepancies between the breed that is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Dodge is a fun, loving, and playful German Shepherd mix.  He’s 10 months old, and weighs 46 lbs.  Dodge loves to play and is very smart and a quick learner. He’s a big cuddle bug and loves to be showered with love and attention. He is crate trained and almost fully housebroken. Dodge plays well with his foster mom’s 1.5 year old female hound/pit mix rescue.  When he’s not playing with his “sister”, Dodge has a very calm temperament and will lay down and chew on his horn or antler or play with a toy. He is working on leash training, and making progress. Dodge knows commands…come, sit, and load in (to his crate).  He will do well in a home with no small children because of his energy and he can be wary of men at first. Dodge is a beautiful love bug who is ready to steal your heart and give you his!.  He’s a great dog and with a little work, patience and commitment, he will be the perfect dog in no time.
If you are interested in this dog, please submit an application directly to our website at www.ny-petrescue.org. Only applications submitted directly to Petrescue will be considered.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Bruno!  I'm about 5 months old. When my foster mom got me I wasn't feeling well,  she took me to the vet and found out I had Parvo. I immediately got treatment. I was able to kick Parvo's booty. Then I came down with bronchitis,  I have finished my antibiotics and am feeling great!!! I have a foster sister(female pit) that I love to play with and also live with two 13 year olds humans that love to snuggle with me. I learned that if I sit pretty I get treats, and I really love treats. I am working on going potty outside. I still have accidents in the house, but I dont potty in my kennel.  I am ready to find my forever home. If you want to meet me let my foster mom know and we will set up a meet and greet. 
Odessa Mo. 
 Fixed and up to date on vet care. Also microchipped $175.  
  Bruno is said to be German shepherd and Pit mix, but we really don't know. He is is a doll! Super sweet personality.  Adopters need to be fully ready for puppy stage and training.
 Please fill out an application. You can find it on our website friendsofthefriendless.co

Meet Polina and Glafira - 2  sisters 

They must be adopted together after what they went through together: hunger, cold weather and etc for been outside since they were small puppies and lost of their mother, another reason for them to be together for life Polina is extremely attached to Glafira. 

Pollina, white/black/tan - 37 Lbs. and Glafira, black/tan/some white - 40 Lbs. 
are 2 bonded sisters.  These mixed-breed puppies are 11 months old.
Once settled in their new home, this friendly pair like to play “fetch” with balls and toys, 
and will enjoy running around a nearby park or fenced-in yard.  
They like other dogs and cats and may sleep nearby or in a person’s bed.
Polly and Ginny have not had experience being around young children.  

These 2 sisters, rescued from the streets, are looking for a “forever” home together.  
Both young female dogs are spayed, up to date with shots.
For more information, contact Marina at: dsprescue@gmail.com or (617) 921-9888.

Zena is a 12 week old Labrador Retriever & Great Dane mix, weighing 21 pounds (on 1.30). She's reported to be mostly housetrained and is working on leash training. She's super energetic and active. She's feisty and loves to play with her toys. She's confident and outgoing. She's very loving, affectionate, and cuddly. She gets along well with other dogs but plays rough and can be too much for little dogs. Be aware that she's a puppy and chews and has sharp teeth and nails. animal.description:
Rover looks to be a 1-2 year old male Catahoula mix, about 55 lbs - very striking with his gold eyes and white & black with brown merle markings. He is a very friendly boy, good leash manners, rather laid back, BUT if he gets loose he may bolt and has selective hearing so then not come back to you. This means he must have a well-fenced yard to keep him safe. Good with other dogs.

ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
Well hello, my name is Hannah. I was saved from New Mexico a few months back with my 5 month old puppy. I ended up being pregnant again (surprise!) and had 6 more adorable babies. They have all found their homes and now its my turn. When I first came into rescue I was really scared and shy. I was also very protective of my babies, so it made it difficult to work on socializing me. But the past few weeks I've really been coming out of my shell. Turns out I LOVE dogs! I love to play chase, and wrestle - I have a fairly rough and rowdy playstyle with another dog that plays the same way - but also tone it down and just throw playbows at the more mellow dogs. I prefer female humans, but am learning that the male ones aren't too bad either (as long as they have lots of treats). I am very food motivated which is helpful. I am trusted loose in the house, and am a really good girl inside, I usually just sit and stare out the window. But then as soon as we go outside, playtime is on! I'm looking for a loving home that will be patient with me as I continue learning and socializing. Another friendly dog my size would be great too!

https://www.facebook.com/thegooddogrescue/videos/1844508895705399

Due to the current events, the rescue is not able to host adoption events. Please fill out an application and we will conduct phone interviews and set up outdoor meet and greets! www.thegooddogrescue.org

My adoption fee is $250 and I will am spayed, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Leena!Leena and Neenah are two playful, adorable puppies in need of loving homes. They love to cuddle and would make great additions to any family. Mom was a mixed breed dog and Dad was a 'traveling salesman', so their mix is based on an educated guess. Leena is the larger of the two and may mature around 50lbs.IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTION, PLEASE READ ALL ADOPTION INFORMATION BELOW!*SPECIAL INFO REGARDING COVID-19 AND PET ADOPTIONSDue to the current public health concerns, our animals are only available for private meetings in Murphysboro, Illinois (no 'adoption events' at this time). We are providing scheduled meetings with one staff member and the pet you are interested in, and asking that adopters bring as few people with them to the meeting as possible, for the health and safety of our staff and your family. Face coverings are required during all interactions with our staff, and we will observe social distancing during the meeting. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we all work together to stay safe and healthy while finding loving homes for the animals in our program.
APPLY AT: www.DogsFromMars.net!Applications are usually processed within ONE BUSINESS DAY. Once approved, you will be able to schedule a meeting with an available animal!

Our shelter is located in southern Illinois, and our animals are available for meetings in Murphysboro, IL, by appointment.

ADOPTION FEE: $300INCLUDES*:(these items have already been completed by the time puppies are listed online)
AT LEAST 3 Wellness ChecksALL 3 PUPPY SHOTS (Distemper/Adenovirus Type-2/ParaInfluenza/Parvovirus)Bordetella Vaccination (kennel cough prevention) + Booster4 month Distemper/Parvo Booster (for puppies 16 weeks and older)At least 2 fecal screenings (to check for intestinal parasites and bacteria)At least 3 Rounds of DewormerPre-adoption 'spa treatment' (bath, conditioning treatment, nail trim, ear cleaning)Microchip ImplantationSecondary Microchip Registration*Complete medical records are available for each puppy at our events and upon adoption.Adoption fees also help to provide a safe and healthy enviroment for the animals in our program, transportation to our shelter, and transportation to our adoption events or meetings.
MARS pets will receive a FREE first exam and 50% spay/neuter discount at Animal Hospital at the Crossing in Champaign, IL (217)356-6387!

animal.description:
Sex: Female 
Approximate Age: 1 year
Size: Medium (approximately 58lbs)
Activity Level: Moderate-high
Breed: Labrador Retriever/ Shepherd mix

Bio:
Hello, my name is Betty! I’m a part of the Northern Outreach Initiative here at Animal Services. I’m such a sweet girl! I love people so much! I’m just a bundle of fun! I’m very wiggly and active. I can’t wait to have lots of outdoor adventures with my new family. I think I could fit in well with just about anyone. Please ask about me today!

Leash: Needs some work
Obedience: Needs training
Containment: A fenced in yard
With other Dogs: Appears ok
With cats: Unknown
With small children: Unknown

Adoption comes with:

* Mandatory spaying/neutering
* First license
* Veterinarian check-up
* First vaccinations
* Tattoo
* Microchip implant
* 6 weeks of free pet insurance
* Small bag of dog food
* De-worming for young pups
 * Literature on responsible pet ownership.

------------------------------------

** IMPORTANT NOTICE **
Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, dog adoptions are currently being done by appointment only. Contact 311 to schedule an appointment. Thank you!

______________________________

Come Meet Our Adoptable Dogs...
Winnipeg Animal Services Agency
1057 Logan Avenue
Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada
R3E 3N8

Phone: 311 - outside Winnipeg dial 1-877-311-4974 

Email: animalservicesagency@winnipeg.ca

Our hours for adoption are Monday to Friday from 11:00 am - 5:30 pm
Saturday & Sunday from 12:00 pm - 4:30pm.
Animal Services is closed on statutory holidays.

BACKGROUND
Almost all the dogs at Animal Services are picked up as strays running loose on the streets of Winnipeg and therefore they come to us with no known history. For this reason, we are not sure how they will interact with other dogs, cats or how they are with children. We would suggest that if you have younger children you bring them down with you to meet the dogs. We also have an outdoor play area where we can do introductions with any other dogs that live in the home.

All locally adopted dogs come with a 7 day home trial. If you return the dog within this time period, you will be refunded your adoption fee less the non-refundable deposit.

Please feel free to meet all the dogs and puppies outside of their kennels, just let the kennel attendants know that you would like a meet and greet with the dog outside of his pen. The dogs are much more relaxed when outside of their kennels. They would love to meet you!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Online Adoption Application 
Squishy face cutie!!Leo will be heading to CARE the weekend of 2/6/2021 and will be ready for adoption once he arrives. Leo's foster mom will post more once he arrives (if not already adopted), but here is what we know! Leo is a young male probably large breed puppy - guessing a Shar pro/ shepherd mix. He was born on/around 9/15/2020 - so he is just shy of 4-5 months old. As a young pup, Leo will need an active home with plenty of time with his humans and space for excercise, play and socializing. His approved adopter will need to have time, patience, financial resources and interest to care for, provide proper veterinary care and work on positive reinforcement training to teach him all he needs to know to be a perfect little gentleman: potty training, crate training, leash walking and general good dog manners.
CARE's adoption fee is $250 for dogs/puppies and $100 for cats/kittens and an additional $150 neuter deposit will be required for any animals adopted prior to their spay/neuter surgery (and the deposit will be refunded when the approved adopter brings the animal to his/her CARE vet appointment in COLUMBUS, INDIANA once scheduled). All CARE animals arrive in their forever homes current on age appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, as well as microchipped and spay/neutered (or scheduled for the same). If you are interested in adopting or meeting a CARE animal, the FIRST STEP is to complete and submit an online adoption application through care.rescuegroups.org.

CARE is an all-volunteer and foster-based rescue organization. We do not have a shelter facility and do not have any employees monitoring inbound applications and emails. Applications are reviewed by each animal's volunteer foster home. It may be several days before you hear from this animal's foster home. Thank you for your patience and understanding as our foster volunteers work to navigate a very high volume of inbound adoption applications.

animal.description:
Charlotte was a stray she is almost 80 pounds of love and affection. Charlotte seems to be a goo with the flow type of girl.  She walks well on a leash, but does not know any commands.  Charlotte does not jump up on you and love to curl up on her bed her.  She is around 4 years old.  Charlotte is looking for a relaxing life where she can chill and watch Netflix.  She loves getting affection and will stand and get any love she can.  She is gentle and easy going.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out an online application at  http://guernseysheriff.com/dog-shelter/  Completed adoption application does not guarantee adoption approval!! 
      Thank you for looking at dogs from the Guernsey County Dog Warden Dept. We are a county run facility in Cambridge, OH, We are NOT a no kill shelter! Unfortunately we must euthanize due to illness or aggression. Adoption fees are $125 for Guernsey County adopters and $160 for dogs adopted out of Guernsey County and Cell Dogs are $185. This includes spay/neuter, first shots, rabies, and microchip!  Most dogs will be required to be  spayed/ neutered before leaving shelter or a appointment will be scheduled before leaving the shelter.   Please talk to shelter staff for more information. 
     We only accept cash. We cannot take checks, debit or credit cards. You may also call the shelter between the hours of 9-5 Mon through Fri and 9-4 on Saturday, for more information and our fax number if you would like us to fax you an application.  You can also visit the shelter between the hours of 11-4 Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday.  If coming from out of town, please call first to make sure the dog you are interested in is still available. Approved rescues also welcome!!!!

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

animal.description: This handsome stud here is Bronco. We are still getting to know Bronco since he came to us from another shelter, but from what we have seen so far this young fellow loves to play be it with toys or his people. Bronco is young and full of energy, plus he has size to go with that energy weighing in around 75 pounds. If you think you would like to potentially make Bronco a part of your family please email the Canine Department at jrein@carrollcountymd.gov to request an application for approval. Once we have approved applications received for him we will reach out to the approved adopter to set up a meet and greet. Bronco does still need to be neutered so he would go home as a foster to adopt until his neuter surgery. Bronco's adoption fee is $200.00 which will also cover his neuter surgery. Since Bronco came in to the other shelter as a stray it is unknown how he would do with children, cats or other dogs.

animal.description: This cute little nugget is Duke! And Duke wants everyone to know that he is all the good doggo things: Housetrained. Sweet. Curious. Silly. Playful. Duke can be a little afraid of new things but he is really a brave boy underneath... he just needs you to show him that it's all okay. He's discovered that riding in the car is pretty awesome, and hiking is fun (as long as there are lots of water breaks!). Duke is also a toy connoisseur and while he prefers rope toys, a squeaky toy will do just fine! Oh, you'd like to play tug of war? Yes! And there are treats in your pocket? He's happy to sample them! Is it snuggle time already? He is happy to oblige! If you'd like to follow Duke's adventures, his Instagram handle is: https://instagram.com/adoptable_duke/ Duke has been living it up in foster and his absolute, without a doubt, #1 thing to do is play with his foster doggy sister! We know that it's important for Duke to have a doggy companion who likes to play as much as he does, and we also know he'd love a yard to run around in. Duke would likely be too much doggo for younger kiddos, but some active teenagers would be great for him! Duke is a member of the Orange Dot Crew (a volunteer advocacy group at Austin Animal Center) so he will go home with their support, as well as a crate, goody bag, and a free training voucher. Please reach out to his foster dad if you would like to learn more about Duke: aelonge11@gmail.com Click here to view my paperwork.

animal.description: My back story is unknown, but I found my way to a secondary highway in Wyoming, where a lovely couple found me and took me in. They drove around looking for a ranch that I may have come from, but there was nothing. After two days they noticed I was lethargic and vomiting, and brought me to the Summit County shelter. I was brought to a local vet clinic, and my diagnosis was parvovirus. UGH! I may die! I took another truck ride to a hospital in Denver, and I stayed, under their care, until I was out of the woods. I came back up to the mountains, and have been living(INSIDE!), and leaning how to walk on leash, and pottying outside. I am approximately 6 months old, around 40 pounds, and fearful of the big wide world. I met another dog at my foster home and cowered and belly crawled. I am now not shedding the virus, and will be getting vetted on Thursday. Then I can find my perminant home. Call the shelter if you want to meet me in my foster home.

animal.description:
Meet Jackie!
This sweet lady has had a rough go since she was a small puppy. She originally  came from Texas and was a shy  little girl. She was with another rescue and they worked to find her the perfect home for almost a year. When they finally thought they  found it they noticed she started to limp on one of her back legs. They brought her to their vet and found out she had bad hip dysplasia and bilateral locating patellas (mobile knee caps). This caused extreme instabilility  and discomfort in her rear end. When they were given the quote for surgery they  simply could not swing it. They reached out to us for help and we transferred her to our rescue. They knew that she was super shy and would do best with them as the foster. We have done surgery to correct both knees. Her hips should be just fine know that her knees have been corrected but she will need to be on joint supplements long term. She also needs to remain on the thin side. She is now ready  for her forever home! Here is what her foster has to say about her and what they feel would be the best fit for this 30# beauty!
"She's still awfully timid in new places, or new places with new people, but she's done exceptional meeting strangers in our own home so I'm confident an understanding and somewhat patient family can earn her trust quickly. 
She has a crazy amount of energy and she's very picky about pooping outside on a leash (another trait her mom and all siblings share too ?) so I personally would require a fenced yard. She's does great with cats and loves to play with them but occasionally needs reminding when she's in a cat's face who isn't into it. She's done well with every dog she's met and she pretty much needs a companion for her play time and energy lol. 
She has destructive tendencies, especially when left alone, even if we go to another floor of the house without her for 15+ minutes. More space and time to get her energy out will likely help. She tolerates the crate and we prefer having her in a wire pen when we do leave and she does well there. 
She definitely needs a family who is into having the dog on the bed because she is constantly up, moving, getting into trouble all night long, unless she's up on the bed, where she'll sleep like a baby typically at the foot of the bed all night.  She can't jump very high so we have to lift her into the car or on the bed but she can handle the couch. 
Ultimately I think she'd do best with a family who is willing to earn her trust and lead her safely through her fears, are aware of her medical history and future, isn't out of the home for long hours (<8 hours a day for sure until she consistently potties outside), and have a fenced yard that will help with her house training, working off her belly, getting all her energy out, and destroying less. Having a current doggy that enjoys wrestling with other dogs would be a huge plus. 
Overall, Jackie is timid and has some behaviors to work on but she has a huge heart and is happiest when she's snuggling and licking her person. Oh yeah, adoptive family MUST love kisses, because she will shower you with them, even when you least expect it ?
Adoption applications available at rpaw.org
Adoption fee is $225

animal.description:
All dogs listed as on HOLD are NOT available for viewing by the public, unless you are their owner. 
Once a dog is no longer on HOLD, it is able to be viewed by the public, participate in meet & greets, and be adopted!

Adoption cost per dog is $99.00 (puppies under 6 months of age are $150.00). The adoption fee includes the following: OH license good for this calendar year, DA2PP, Bordetella vaccine, Heartworm testing, dewormer, and spay/neuter.  Flea treatment will be provided if fleas are noticed.  All dogs will be spayed/neutered and microchipped before leaving the facility.  An e-collar may be purchased for $15.00.  Because most of our dogs were picked up as strays, we have no knowledge of any behavior or health issues.  Stray dogs are held for 72 hours so that the owners have a chance to redeem them. After that time they are vetted and placed up for adoption. We welcome and encourage the cross posting of our dog's pictures to increase adoptions.

This sweet little fuzzy boy is CHIPOTLE, a shy mixed breed boy looking for a furever home. Chipotle is 1 year old and fully grown at 22 lbs. His breed mix is a mystery. He has a medium-length coat. Maybe some Brittany? Beagle? He's likely a mix of multiple breeds. Chipotle is a timid little guy who needs a patient adopter who will help build his confidence. He's house broken and crate trained, fine with other dogs and cats. He's best suited to a home with another friendly confident dog and a physically-fenced yard. He would be okay in a home with older kids but no small children because they make him nervous. Chipotle is not well suited to apartment living. If you'd like to meet Chipotle, please fill out a foster to adopt application at
dreamhouserescue.org.
Greater Cincinnati adopters only please. We will ONLY consider applications from adopters with another friendly dog and a physically fenced yard. No apartments.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.

animal.description:
Meet Murphy, a 6-year-old, 60 lb., Retriever mix!
Murphy is an exceptional dog—calm, obedient, eager to please and well-trained. He can be a couch potato most of the day, but ready anytime for a run, walk or to play fetch with his beloved ball. Most people actually think he’s still a young pup, despite being 6 years old. 

His recent bloodwork was excellent and he recently had his teeth cleaned. Murphy is very healthy, up to date on vaccines and heartworm negative. He has been kept on Nexgard and Heartgard Plus each month. 

He’s okay to be alone, uncrated in the house, while someone is out or at work. He’s completely house-trained, doesn’t ever touch any possessions in the home
 and has never been destructive. He won’t even touch food left on the counter. He's the perfect gentleman in the home! 
Murphy knows his commands and will sit and stay when guests arrive at the door and will even sit and stay while given his meals. 

Murphy has a submissive personality around other dogs but he is also good as an only pet. All told, he could easily win the "best all round" category 
in the world of dog superlatives. He's a wonderful family pet!  If you are interested in learning more about Murphy, please email  adoptsch@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Please meet Sheeba!  This pretty Border Collie mix pup was surrendered by her owner after she began chasing their chickens….just couldn’t help the herding instinct.  Sheeba is now happily living in foster care (where there are no chickens…lol) and receiving lots of TLC while waiting for a place to hang her leash forever.

Sheeba is 6 months and weighs in a 46 pounds.  Her mix is a best guess, but considering her size at this age there’s likely a larger breed in her DNA.  Typical of border collies, she is an energetic, smart girl and will do best in an active home where she’ll get plenty of regular exercise and stimulation.  She is house trained and crate trained.  Also enjoys going for rides and is very well behaved in the car.
 
This lovable, happy  girl gets along great with other dogs.  She doesn’t seem to know what to think about cats.  She might do okay with a dog-savvy kitty; however, with that herding instinct, she’d probably chase a cat that runs.  There are no children in her foster home but she’s a very affectionate pup who loves her humans so we think she would love to be part of a family with kids 8 or over.  Though she would not intentionally harm anyone, playful, energetic pups can accidently knock little ones down.

Sheeba has been spayed and is up to date on vaccines.  She’s also micro-chipped and on monthly flea/tick and heart worm preventative.  Her doggy bag is packed and she’s all set to head for her forever home.  If you have the time to devote to an energetic playful pup like Sheeba, please email Chris at rescue3@earthlink.net for an application.  Her adoption fee is $400. 

Like us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/pawsclawsnewengland
Follow/tag us on Instagram: @pawsclawsne or #pawsclawsne

Shelby was a stray. She is a sweet girl.  She has the cutest little face with her silly ears that make her that much more adorable.   Shelby weight 13 pounds.  She enjoys cuddling and snuggling in a warm blanket.  We think shelby is around 5 years old.  She has not had much to say about being her.  It is definitely stressful for her and she has not been eating very well.  Shelby is looking for love and companionship.  

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out an online application at  http://guernseysheriff.com/dog-shelter/  Completed adoption application does not guarantee adoption approval!! 
      Thank you for looking at dogs from the Guernsey County Dog Warden Dept. We are a county run facility in Cambridge, OH, We are NOT a no kill shelter! Unfortunately we must euthanize due to illness or aggression. Adoption fees are $125 for Guernsey County adopters and $160 for dogs adopted out of Guernsey County and Cell Dogs are $185. This includes spay/neuter, first shots, rabies, and microchip!  Most dogs will be required to be  spayed/ neutered before leaving shelter or a appointment will be scheduled before leaving the shelter.   Please talk to shelter staff for more information. 
     We only accept cash. We cannot take checks, debit or credit cards. You may also call the shelter between the hours of 9-5 Mon through Fri and 9-4 on Saturday, for more information and our fax number if you would like us to fax you an application.  You can also visit the shelter between the hours of 11-4 Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday.  If coming from out of town, please call first to make sure the dog you are interested in is still available. Approved rescues also welcome!!!!

animal.description:
Age: 11 Months 
Weight: 38 lbs.
Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats:  Not Tested
Good with kids:  Yes
Energy Level: Med-High
Available for Adoption: 2/6/2021 (Currently accepting applications).
Applications need to be approved before a meet and greet will be set up for any Fetching Hearts Rescue dogs. 

Meet Missy!!!  This sweet girl was brought in by her family who could no longer care for her.  Missy loves doing zoomies in the backyard while throwing her toys in the air.   She enjoys having doggie friends to run around with.  Missy will need a family or couple who will take her on hikes or do outdoor activities with her.  She would do well with a fenced yard.  Missy does great with kids and dogs.  She would love to also meet her new family when she arrives up north this weekend.  She might not know exactly what snow is all about, but she is ready to learn about it and pounce around in it.  Let's give Missy her forever home she deserves.  She has lots of love to give!!!!

If interested in Missy, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online
to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination.

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter.
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ: The clinics are not open for viewing animals. Since we currently can't meet you in person, if you are interested in meeting this pet, please email information about yourself, family, residence and current/prior pet experience. If it is a good fit you will be emailed an application. Once that is approved, arrangements will be made for a meeting. Thanks for your understanding!

Watson is an approximately 12 week old male Jack Russell (?) Mix who we believe will stay under 25 lbs as an adult. Watson has a short naturally docked tail. Unfortunately we don't know either parent so we can't say for sure what breed mix they are and ultimately what size they will be but this is our best guess. Watson and his littermates were rescued from a Kentucky shelter when their time was up. His adoption fee is $399 and includes his neuter, vaccinations, microchip and routine labwork. Please email us to start the adoption process.

For puppies 6 months and younger you must live within 50 miles of Oswego, IL.

Email inquires can be directed to availablepets@gmail.com
Adoption donations for adult dogs range from $59 to $299 and puppies from $159 to $599. This includes: 
-  Spay or neuter surgery
Vaccines current to the date of adoption*: 
  -  Rabies vaccine
  -  Bordatella vaccine
  -  Booster for canine Distemper, Adenovirus type 1 & 2, Leptospirosis,
      Parainfluenza, Parvovirus, and Coronavirus (DHLPPC)
  - Canine Influenza vaccine
-  Fecal test
-  1st worming 
-  Heartworm test (+6 months old) 
-  Capstar flea treatment
-  Microchip identification implant
* Boosters required for puppies and kittens (depending on age) POST adoption are the responsibility of the pet owner.
 
Heartworm prevention must also be purchased at the time of adoption and prices vary depending on the size of the animal being adopted.  Puppies under 6 months old are required to sign up for a puppy obedience class. ($89 deposit required, refundable upon completion)

Come Ready to Adopt: 
If you rent or live in a condo/townhouse with an association, bring your lease/bylaws indicating pets are allowed and if there are any restrictions. We require vaccinations and tests to be up to date for the protection of your current pets. Bringing their vet records can help speed the adoption process. All adults in the household must be present and co-sign the application.

animal.description:
Mickey came to us from the Sheriff's Office and was not reclaimed. 
He is a little rough and rambunctious with other dogs so a meet and greet will definitely be required to make sure your dog likes him. When we introduced him to the cats, he did not pay much attention to them at all and when they swatted at him, he just moved away.
He is a barker-if he thinks you should be paying attention to him, he will let you know. So he is not someone you would want to leave out for long periods of time because he thrives on attention and love from people. 

He is nice medium size and we think he will make an excellent hiking/walking adventure buddy. Anytime spent with his people, he thrives on.

animal.description:
*Please research Cushing's Disease prior to applying for Heidi. She has a life long medical condition that requires daily medication.* 

My name is Heidi and I have a story to tell. A little over a year ago I was found in a home with another dog, abandoned by our family. Luckily, we were rescued shortly after and made our way to a rescue group. I was then brought to Wisconsin and placed in an adoptive home. Unfortunately, it wasn't the best match and I was surrendered to the Neenah Animal Shelter. 
It's difficult to see in the photo, but I am almost entirely bald with a few hair scruffs on my head and back. This is also my first time exploring the outdoors in almost 7 months since I was puppy pad trained in my previous home. The shelter feels I'm too big to potty inside, so they make me go outside. I will need help with potty training and frequent bathroom breaks (every couple of hours).

I went to the vet for a check up because NAS knew that my lack of hair was a sign of medical concern. Well, after an 8 hour testing process I was diagnosed with Cushing's Disease. I won't bore you with all the medical details, but basically my pituitary or adrenal gland are not working correctly which is causing an overproduction of cortisol in my body. This causes hair loss, bloating, and increased thirst/hunger, and a few other things.

What does this mean for me? I will be on a medication called Vetoryl for life and will need to maintain a close relationship with my veterinarian as blood work rechecks will be needed regularly to monitor the disease. Aside from that, I will live a happy normal life. 

Now, more about me and not my disease. To put it simply, I am a 20 pound potato that must sit on your lap at ALL TIMES! I am not exaggerating when I say that I will be glued to your hip. I am happiest when my people are home with me, but I can survive for a few hours on my own. I only bark when I know someone is nearby and not paying attention to me. I get along well with cats and other small dogs (haven't met too many larger ones). I haven't been around children much, but as long as they have a lap to sit on I'm sure we'll get along. I will admit that keeping my Cushing's in check can be expensive because of the medication and frequent vet visits, but I promise I am worth every penny. 

Please note:
- Our website (www.neenahanimalshelter.org) is updated in real time, so we are accepting applications for all animals that are currently listed.
-Applications can be downloaded from our website. (http://neenahanimalshelter.org/how-to-adopt.html)
- Our shelter no longer has open visiting hours, so a pre-approved application and scheduled appointment is needed prior to meeting any of our animals.
animal.name: Heidi *special needs*

animal.description: Don't let her name fool you; Snow will make your heart melt. This beautiful ice princess is Snow! Snow came to us when her previous owner was not able to take care of her, so she found her way to us so that we can set her up with her forever family! Snow has lived with cats and is said to be very friendly and playful with other dogs. She is so incredibly smart, and even though she is just a pup, she already knows most basic commands. Snow needs someone who is going to be able to handle her energy and provide her with an active lifestyle so she does not get bored. In her previous home she did have a tendency to be destructive when left alone. However, with the proper attention and mental stimulation, she is well prepared to be your best friend ! Snow is nervous around new people and we do not know if she has lived with children, we are recommending she go home to children 10 and up as well as no apartments so she can roam around and get some of her energy out! If you are interested in this sweet girl, please contact a kennel technician.

animal.description:
Lovely Leonard, a mellow gentleman 
He's sweet and loving. Enjoys going for a long lumber and playing with his toys. He is a snuggly guy and has wonderful companion manners. He would enjoy a large living space with space to romp around roll about. He may do well with another canine friend and whilst appropriate with cats, will be very forward and may need some feline correction! 

Leonard is currently hanging out at the shelter while waiting for a foster home. See instructions below on how to send in an application to come meet him.

To meet Leonard, send an application (found here) http://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/AnimalShelter/Dog%20Adoption%20Questionnaire_Fillable.pdf to animalcare@seattle.gov - thanks!
